'''STREETS International''', is a New York based U.S. 501(c)(3), [[non-profit]] corporation, founded to provide culinary and hospitality training for street kids, orphans and other disadvantaged youth across [[South East Asia]].<ref name="planetwheeler">{{cite web|title=STREETS International|url=http://www.planetwheeler.org/index.php?id=47|publisher=Planet Wheeler}}</ref> STREETS International is a self sustaining [[initiative]] with all the revenues from the STREETS Restaurant Caf<U+00E9> going to support the program.<ref name=Concierge.com>{{cite web|last=Chen|first=Mollie|title=Streets International Takes Kids from the Streets to the Kitchen|url=http://www.concierge.com/cntraveler/blogs/80days/2009/03/streets-interna.html|publisher=Concierge.com}}</ref>  

== Program ==
STREETS was established in 2007 and opened it<U+2019>s Hoi An Restaurant Caf<U+00E9> in 2009. It provides a comprehensive an 18-month training program that  follows a curriculum developed in conjunction with the [[Institute of Culinary Education]] in [[New York]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ICE Supports STREETS International's Culinary Education Programs for Asian Street Kids|url=http://www.iceculinary.com/news/press/press_70.shtml|publisher=Institute of Culinary Education}}</ref>  Graduates finish the program with an international certificate in the hospitality and culinary fields.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tiger Airways Supports STREETS International to empower street kids in SE Asia|url=http://www.tigerairways.com/news/TR_20101110_Tiger_Airways_supports_Streets_International_to_empower_street_kids_in_SE_Asia.pdf}}</ref>  The program provides the necessary daily living support for participants -- called <U+2018>Trainees.<U+2019> This includes supervised housing, food, financial support and basic medical care. Trainees are selected from throughout [[Vietnam]]; program participants typically are orphaned or come from [[extreme poverty]], including those that have been [[trafficked]] or are part of the often overlooked [[Vietnamese ethnic groups|ethnic minority groups]].<ref>{{cite web|title=FOR VIETNAM'S POOREST, STREETS INTERNATIONAL GIVES THEM A FUTURE|url=http://insidefandb.com/2010/05/for-the-vietnam<U+2019>s-poorest-streets-international-gives-them-a-future/}}</ref> 

STREETS<U+2019> goal is to match the needs of [[disadvantaged]] [[youth]] with the opportunities in growing [[tourism]] [[economies]], by providing job training,  [[English language]] instruction and life skills education.

== STREETS Restaurant Caf<U+00E9> ==
Program participants apprentice at the STREETS Restaurant Caf<U+00E9> located at 17 Le Loi Street in the central historic district of [[Hoi An]], [[Quang Nam province]], [[Vietnam]].<ref name="planetwheeler" /> All proceeds from the STREETS Restaurant Caf<U+00E9> help support the Training Program and other costs. The STREETS Restaurant Caf<U+00E9> is listed in [[Lonely Planet|The Lonely Planet]]'s Dining for a Cause, Vietnam section.<ref name="Lonely Planet">{{cite web|last=Wheeler|first=Tashi|title=Dining for a Cause|url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/vietnam/travel-tips-and-articles/12039|publisher=Lonely Planet}}</ref> Many articles have been published about the Restaurant and the project including features in ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref name="online" /> ''Gourmet Live'',<ref name="Gourmet Live" /> ''Brandeis Magazine''<ref name="Brandeis Magazine">{{cite web|last=Gardner|first=Laura|title=Dishing Up Success|url=http://streetsinternational.org/news-and-press-streets-international/100-brandeis.html|accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref> and ''Aviation''.<ref>{{cite web|title=STREETS International Offers More Than Hospitality|url=http://streetsinternational.org/news-and-press-streets-international/74-aviation.html|publisher=Aviation|accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref>  

== Trainee selection ==
Trainees for the STREETS program are selected for each new class every nine months. Applicants come from all across Vietnam to be accepted into the program that supports between 15 and 20 Trainees per class. All applicants have disadvantaged backgrounds and are between 16 to 22 years old.<ref name="Gourmet Live">{{cite web|title=10 Questions for Neal Bermas|url=http://www.gourmet.com/food/gourmetlive/2011/092811/10-questions-for-neal-bermas|publisher=Gourmet Live}}</ref>

== Self-Sustaining Program ==
The organization goal is to be fully self-supporting, although there is an initial capital for each program site.<ref name="online">{{cite web|last=West|first=Melanie Grayce|title=Off the Streets, Into the Kitchen|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052702303816504577309950235340114.html|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref>  Funding is also made possible by individual, corporate and foundation support. A Trainee Sponsorship program and fundraising events in the United States provide additional support.

